Graphics in R: ggplot2

Introduction

There are 3 main environments in R to create graphics:

  • R base utilities
  • lattice package
  • ggplot2 package

There is also powerful “grid” package and a couple in-development interactive packages

In this tutorial we will concentrate on a popular ggplot2 library from tidyverse (https://www.tidyverse.org/)

Cheatsheet

The Philosophy of Visualization

The Grammar of Graphics by Leland Wilkinson

“The grammar of graphics takes us beyond a limited set of charts (words) to an almost unlimited world of graphical forms (statements)…The rules of graphics grammar are sometimes mathematical and sometimes aestheic. Mathematics provides symbolic tools for representing abstractions. Aesthetics, in the original Greek sense, offers principles for relating sensory attributes (color, shape, sound, etc.) to abstractions.”

Object Oriented Design

  • Procedural vs Object Orientation
  • Procedural approaches to a problem break the problem into a series of dependent steps whereas object orientation classifies the problem into independent components that summarize the problem.
  • 3 Stages of Graphics Creation:
    1. Specification
    2. Assembly
    3. Display

“Once we understand that a pie is a divided bar in polar coordinates, we can construct other polar graphics that are less well known.”

ggplot2 vs Base R

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(pressure,aes(x=temperature,y=pressure)) + geom_point()

plot(pressure)

Base R plots two vectors as x and y axes and allows modifications to that representation of data whereas ggplot2 derives graphics directly from the dataset. This allows faster fine-tuning of visualizations of data rather than representations of data stitched together in the Base R package1.

The Grammar of ggplot2

A Simple Introduction to the Graphing Philosophy of ggplot2 by Tom Hopper

Each plot is comprised of the basic elements:

  1. Data: Raw data to be illustrated
  2. Layers/Geometries: Plots or shapes representating the data
  3. Aesthetics: Aesthetics of the illustration including colors, size, shapes, and position
  4. Scales: The ranges and options of the aesthetics representing the data

The typical ggplot2 code will look like:

data
+ geometry to represent the data,
+ aesthetic mappings of data to plot coordinates like position, color and size
+ scaling of ranges of the data to ranges of the aesthetics

With the advanced options:

  1. Statistical Transformations: Statistical summaries, e.g. regression lines, quantiles
  2. Coordinate Systems: Transform the axes to a new dimension, e.g. circular x-axis
  3. Visual Themes: Use themes to adjust the labels, background, lengend, etc.

Factors & Levels

Factors are categorical data objects stored as levels, e.g. “Male/Female”, “True/False”. ggplot2 will sort and order based on levels if dataframe contains factors.

df = data.frame(grades=c('A','A','C','B'),students=c('Katia','Brian','Dustin','Christoper'))
str(df)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ grades  : Factor w/ 3 levels "A","B","C": 1 1 3 2
##  $ students: Factor w/ 4 levels "Brian","Christoper",..: 4 1 3 2
df = data.frame(grades=c('A','A','C','B'),students=c('Katia','Brian','Dustin','Christoper'),stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
str(df)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ grades  : chr  "A" "A" "C" "B"
##  $ students: chr  "Katia" "Brian" "Dustin" "Christoper"
df$grades = factor(df$grades)
str(df)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ grades  : Factor w/ 3 levels "A","B","C": 1 1 3 2
##  $ students: chr  "Katia" "Brian" "Dustin" "Christoper"
levels(df$grades) = c("Yay!","OK","Ehh")
str(df)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ grades  : Factor w/ 3 levels "Yay!","OK","Ehh": 1 1 3 2
##  $ students: chr  "Katia" "Brian" "Dustin" "Christoper"
df
##   grades   students
## 1   Yay!      Katia
## 2   Yay!      Brian
## 3    Ehh     Dustin
## 4     OK Christoper

data(midwest, package = "ggplot2")
options(scipen=999) # Base R function that controls options for dealing with data - 'scipen' turns off scientific notation

Setting up the Data

  • ggplot needs to know which dataset to use before anything can be drawn onto the graph.
  • Some aesthetics (e.g. x & y axes) can be set either here or in later layers/geometries.
  • The setup can be stored as a variable for building different plots ontop of the same basic setup.
ggplot(midwest) # Load the setup layer (blank plot)

ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) # Load the setup layer with aesthetics specified (labeled grid without data)

g0 = ggplot(midwest,aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) # Save the setup layer as a variable
g0 # Draw the setup layer saved as variable 'g0'

The Layers

ggplot has a number of layers available listed at https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ They include options for:

  • Geometries (e.g. scatterplot, bar charts, contours, text, polygons, etc.)
  • Stats (statistical transformations)
  • Position Adjustment (e.g. dodging, jittering, stacking, etc.)
  • Annotations (add fixed reference data to plots)
ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) + geom_point() # Scatterplot

ggplot(midwest) + geom_point(aes(x = area, y = poptotal))

ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area)) + geom_point(aes(y = poptotal))

g1 = g0 + geom_point()
g1

Regression

geom_smooth or stat_smooth are methods that plot models of the data. Method and formula can be specified, confidence bands can be removed.

ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm')

ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = 'y ~ poly(x,2)')

ggplot(midwest,aes(x=area,y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = 'y ~ poly(x,2)', se = FALSE)

Adjusting Axes

Deleting Data vs Zooming In

  1. Deleting Data: xlim() & ylim() hardcode limits of the axes
g = ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm')

g + xlim(c(0, 0.1) ) + ylim(c(0, 1000000))
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. Zooming In: coord_cartesian() retains all values of attached data to be used in stats layers but only data within provided limits are displayed
g + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000))

Axes Labels

The functions labs() or ggtitle() with xlab()/ylab() control axes labels.

# Build the Setup
g0 = ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal))

# Build the Scatter and Regression Layers
g =  g0 + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm')

# Build the plot with Zoom
g1 = g + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000))

# Add Titles and Labels

g1 + labs(title = "Area v. Population", subtitle = "From the midwest dataset", x = "Area", y = "Population", caption = "Midwest Demographics")

or

g1 + ggtitle("Area v. Population", subtitle = "From the midwest dataset") + xlab("Area") + ylab("Total Population")

Colors

The colors of each layer can be set within the layer depending on the geometry used:

g0 = ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal))
g0 + geom_point(col = "steelblue", size = 3) +    # Label scatterplot points with color 'steelblue' & size 3
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "firebrick") + # Draw the regression line with the color 'firebrick'
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) + labs(title = "Area v. Population", subtitle = "From the midwest dataset", x = "Area", y = "Population", caption = "Midwest Demographics")

The aesthetics function within geometries can attach features (e.g. color,size, shape, stroke, fill) to the layer based on the data:

gg = g0 + geom_point(aes(col = state, size = 3)) +    
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "firebrick", size = 2) + # Change thickness of regression line
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) + labs(title = "Area v. Population", subtitle = "From the midwest dataset", x = "Area", y = "Population", caption = "Midwest Demographics")
gg

Legends drawn by the aestheics within the geometries can be removed:

gg + theme(legend.position = "None")  # Remove legend

gg + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Accent")

The Axes

Different geometries can be added to manipulate the axes’ values and aesthetics depending on the type of data represented by each axis.

  • scale_x_continuous(): x-axis contains continuous values
  • scale_y_date(): y-axis contains date values
  • scale_x_log10(): x-axis contains log base 10 values

Available scales are on the ggplot reference page: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/

The increments of the axes ticks are controlled by breaks and the text is controlled by labels:

gg = g0 + geom_point(aes(col = state, size = 3)) +    
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "firebrick", size = 2) + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) + labs(title = "Area v. Population", subtitle = "From the midwest dataset", x = "Area", y = "Population", caption = "Midwest Demographics")
gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.1, 0.01)) # Break x-axis into 11 ticks by 0.01

Reverse the scale:

gg + scale_x_reverse() # Reverse the x-axis

Change the labels of the x-axis with a vector input to ‘labels’:

gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.1, 0.01), labels = letters[1:11]) # Label x-axis ticks with values of R array 'letters'

Change the labels of the x-axis by formatting the data of the axis:

gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.1, 0.01), labels = sprintf("%1.2f%%", seq(0, 0.1, 0.01))) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1000000, 200000), labels = function(x){paste0(x/1000, 'K')})

Themes

Themes are saved sets of aestheics that can be used as a basis for the visualization. Available themes are listed on the ggplot reference page: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/

theme_set(theme_classic()) # Themes can be set in the background for all visualizations to adopt when drawn
gg

gg + theme_bw() + labs(subtitle = "Black & White Theme") # Or Themes can be built into the existing visualization as a layer

gg + theme_classic() + labs(subtitle = "Classic Theme")

gg <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x=area, y=poptotal)) + 
  geom_point(aes(col=state, size=popdensity)) + 
  geom_smooth(method="loess", se=F) + xlim(c(0, 0.1)) + ylim(c(0, 500000)) + 
  labs(title="Area Vs Population", y="Population", x="Area", caption="Source: midwest")

# Modify theme components -------------------------------------------
gg + theme(plot.title=element_text(size=20, 
                                    face="bold", 
                                    family="American Typewriter",
                                    color="tomato",
                                    hjust=0.5,
                                    lineheight=1.2),  # title
            plot.subtitle=element_text(size=15, 
                                       family="American Typewriter",
                                       face="bold",
                                       hjust=0.5),  # subtitle
            plot.caption=element_text(size=15),  # caption
            axis.title.x=element_text(vjust=10,  
                                      size=15),  # X axis title
            axis.title.y=element_text(size=15),  # Y axis title
            axis.text.x=element_text(size=10, 
                                     angle = 30,
                                     vjust=.5),  # X axis text
            axis.text.y=element_text(size=10))  # Y axis text

labs() v. guides()

gg + labs(color="State", size="Density") # labs()

gg + guides(color=guide_legend("State"), size=guide_legend("Density")) # guides()

Remove aesthetic from individual geometry:

gg <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x=area, y=poptotal)) + 
  geom_point(aes(col=state, size=popdensity)) + 
  geom_smooth(method="loess", se=F) + xlim(c(0, 0.1)) + ylim(c(0, 500000)) + 
  labs(title="Area Vs Population", y="Population", x="Area", caption="Source: midwest")
gg + scale_color_discrete(name = "State") + scale_size_continuous(name = "Density", guide = FALSE) # The aestheic color was given the variable type 'state' and the aestheic size was given the variable type 'popdensity' in geom_point() and can be controlled with the layer object 'scale_<aesthetic>_<variabletype>': turn off legened with 'guide' option

Control individual elements of the labels with scale_color_manual:

gg + scale_color_manual(name="State", 
                        labels = c("Illinois", 
                                   "Indiana", 
                                   "Michigan", 
                                   "Ohio", 
                                   "Wisconsin"), 
                        values = c("IL"="blue", 
                                   "IN"="red", 
                                   "MI"="green", 
                                   "OH"="brown", 
                                   "WI"="orange"))

Use guides() to order the legend:

gg + guides(colour = guide_legend(order = 1), size = guide_legend(order = 2))

element_rect() controls figure like elements, i.e. the legend:

gg + theme(legend.title = element_text(size=12, color = "firebrick"), 
           legend.text = element_text(size=10),
           legend.key = element_rect(fill='springgreen')) + # Fill the legend key background with element_rect()

Annotations

Rules for annotation must be included in a dataset derived or compatible with the data frame originally used to set up ggplot:

midwest_sub <- midwest[midwest$poptotal > 300000, ] # Subset data frame 'midwest' for large populations
midwest_sub$large_county <- ifelse(midwest_sub$poptotal > 300000, midwest_sub$county, "") # Create column with labels for annotations
gg + geom_text(aes(label=large_county), size=2, data=midwest_sub) + labs(subtitle="With ggplot2::geom_text") + theme(legend.position = "None")

gg + geom_label(aes(label=large_county), size=2, data=midwest_sub, alpha=0.25) + labs(subtitle="With ggplot2::geom_label") + theme(legend.position = "None")

# library(ggrepel) will push annotations away from one another for a cleaner look

Add text to plot based on coordinates:

library(grid) # graphics package that adds an nx by ny rectanglular grid to an existing plot
my_text <- "This text is at x=0.7 and y=0.8!"
my_grob = grid.text(my_text, x=0.7,  y=0.8, gp=gpar(col="firebrick", fontsize=14, fontface="bold"))

gg + annotation_custom(my_grob)

Flip Coordinates

gg + coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 15 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Faceting

Draw multiple plots on one figure (new data set):

data(mpg, package = 'ggplot2')

g <- ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) + 
      geom_point() + 
      labs(title="hwy vs displ", caption = "Source: mpg") +
      geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE) + 
      theme_bw()  # apply bw theme
plot(g)

g + facet_wrap( ~ class, nrow=3) + labs(title="hwy vs displ", caption = "Source: mpg", subtitle="Ggplot2 - Faceting - Multiple plots in one figure")

By deafault, the scales for each plot are the same. They can become ‘freed’ for individaul scales for each plot:

g + facet_wrap( ~ class, scales = "free") + labs(title="hwy vs displ", caption = "Source: mpg", subtitle="Ggplot2 - Faceting - Multiple plots in one figure with free scales")

facet_grid() will wrap all variables and avoid crowding of scales inside the plots:

g + facet_grid(manufacturer ~ class) # Set manufacturer as rows and class as columns

  • library(gridExtra) will allow you to wrap facets within facets

Plot Features: Background, Major/Minor Axes

Using the theme option panel gives us control over the many plot features:

g + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = 'khaki'),
          panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "burlywood", size=1.5),
          panel.grid.minor = element_line(colour = "tomato", 
                                          size=.25, 
                                          linetype = "dashed"),
          panel.border = element_blank(),
          axis.line.x = element_line(colour = "darkorange", 
                                     size=1.5, 
                                     lineend = "butt"),
          axis.line.y = element_line(colour = "darkorange", 
                                     size=1.5)) +
    labs(title="Modified Background", 
         subtitle="How to Change Major and Minor grid, Axis Lines, No Border")

# Change Plot Margins -----------------------------------------------
g + theme(plot.background=element_rect(fill="salmon"), 
          plot.margin = unit(c(2, 2, 1, 1), "cm")) +  # top, right, bottom, left
    labs(title="Modified Background", subtitle="How to Change Plot Margin")

Remove everything!

g + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
          panel.border = element_blank(),
          axis.title = element_blank(), 
          axis.text = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks = element_blank()) +
  labs(title="Modified Background", subtitle="How to remove major and minor axis grid, border, axis title, text and ticks")
